I'm not so convinced that we'll get there without a new large discovery. Moore's law is basically dead until someone makes a new breakthrough. Transistors can't be made any smaller and still function and chips can't be made any bigger without literally melting themselves. Some people have talked about graphene transistors being an option but that's still up in the air. I think most of advancements we'll get from here on is in unconventional computation like quantum or biological. Quantum specifically is what I'm researching because it has the potential to open up an entirely new world of material and medical advancements. But there's also significant gains being made in biological stuff like CRISPR and research on fusion power has been going pretty well while they're still trying to get the government to foot the 15-20 billion dollar bill. Personally, I think it'll be more than 50 years before we make real progress towards any of that stuff. All I can hope to do is keep myself healthy and try to make it happen faster.

Like I said, I think the biggest gains will be in running physics simulations. There are tons of open problems in material science where we know how to describe the problem but it's far too complex to solve because it grows exponentially. A very significant portion of scientific advancement is held back by materials problems. People can describe the properties a material needs to fulfill some criteria but we have no clue how to make it. That's in part because we currently can't truly simulate anything more complicated than a 40 electron system, truly meaning quantum effects included. There's definitely a lot of other work that needs to be done though.
